English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Horton was born in 1160, in England, United Kingdom. He had at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1160–":"1160–Surnud","1188–1257":"1188–1257","1190–1273":"1190–1273","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1188":"1188","1273":"1273","1160":"1160","Horton, Northumberland, England":"Horton, Northumberland, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–":"1160–Kuollut","1188–1257":"1188–1257","1190–1273":"1190–1273","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1257":"1257","1188":"1188","1273":"1273","1160":"1160","Horton, Northumberland, England":"Horton, Northumberland, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1160–":"1160–Décédé